====Alternative forms====
* {{l|en|yabbie}}
====Noun====
{{en-noun}}
# {{lb|en|AU}} An Australian [[freshwater crayfish]] of the genus {{taxlink|Cherax|genus|noshow=1}}, especially {{taxlink|Cherax destructor|species|noshow=1}}.
#* '''1985''', {{w|Peter Carey}}, ''Illywhacker'', Faber and Faber 2003, p. 386:
#*: Having arrived at night I can speak with some authority on the desolate feeling the road produces: the white fire-scarred trunks, the unsettling vision of '''yabbies''' moving from one side of the road to the other.
# {{lb|en|Australia}} A species of marine [[ghost shrimp]], {{taxlink|Trypaea australiensis|species|noshow=1}}, widely harvested by recreational [[angler]]s as [[bait]].
#* {{quote-journal|1=en|year=1961|author=Hailstone, T. S.|author2=Stephenson, W.|title=The Biology of ''Callianassa'' (''Trypaea'') ''australiensis'' Dana 1852 (Crustacea, Thalassinidea)|journal=University of Queensland Papers: Department of Zoology|volume=I|issue=12|url=https://espace.library.uq.edu.au/view/UQ:222651/QL1_U7_1961_v1no12.pdf?dsi_version=8ceed487f9d6b699ecacaea8b87f3c37|page=260|text=''Callianassa australiensis'' is known in southern New South Wales as the "ghost-nipper" (Dakin, Bennett and Pope, 1952), and in northern New South Wales and Queensland as the "'''yabby'''" (a word of aboriginal origin also applied to freshwater crayfish).}}
#* {{quote-book|1=en|year=2007|author=McEnally, J.|author2=McEnally, L.|title=Julie & Lawrie McEnally's Complete Book of Fishing Baits & Rigs|chapter=Yabbies (saltwater)|page=70|url=https://www.google.com.au/books/edition/Complete_Book_of_Fishing_Baits_and_Rigs/9qxnIB0oMecC?hl=en&gbpv=1&pg=PA70|text=Putting the '''yabby''' on a hook takes a little care and hook sizes need to match the physical dimensions of the '''yabby'''.}}
#* {{quote-book|1=en|year=2007|author=Woodford, J.|title=Whitecap|chapter=12|page=132|url=https://www.google.com.au/books/edition/Whitecap/B3-eVWRL0cwC?hl=en&gbpv=1&pg=PA132|text=Now she held the net in front of the pump so Penny could empty its contents. The first suck was mud, the second sometimes yielded a couple of '''yabbies''' but on the third, three or four '''yabbies''' nearly always spurted out, flicking their tails, weakly opening and closing their nippers.}}
